"Located in the former Collège des Quatre-Nations, the Institut de France houses two great libraries, the Bibliothèque de l'Institut, reserved for the use of members of the Académie Française and researchers who they recommend, and the Bibliothèque Mazarine. The wealth of the Institute in manuscripts, rare and precious editions, incunables, and ancient books, is not limited to these two collections. Several of the foundations and museums of the Institute of France also have libraries, some of which are of great importance such as the Bibliothèque du Duc d'Aumale at the Château de Chantilly." 

Counts: 500,000 volumes, including 180,000 16th-18th c.; 1500 periodicals titles including 500 current; 2110 incunables; 4639 volumes ms. including 1500 medieval.
